## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Pattern Classification

This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — a thread is aborted if it exceeds a time limit. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is removed entirely.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if the delegate hasn't observed it yet.
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't stop automatically** | `CancellationToken` is *cooperative*. `Task.Run` won't magically kill the delegate. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop, it keeps running in the background. Pass `CancellationToken` into the work itself for true cancellation. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` is `IDisposable` — always wrap in `using`. Leaking it causes timer leaks. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the top-level orchestration point (here, to convert to `TimeoutException`). Don't swallow it deeper in the call chain. |
| **Blocking on async (`GetResult`)** | This preserves the original synchronous API. If you can make callers async, prefer `await` instead. |

### If the work *must* be forcibly killed

If `work()` calls uncooperative code (third-party, native) that can't check a token, **there is no in-process replacement for `Thread.Abort`**. Move the work to a child process and use `Process.Kill()`:

```csharp
// Last resort — only for truly uncooperative code
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("Worker process timed out");
}
```

### Preferred fully-async version

If callers can be made async, this is cleaner:

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

This version passes the token *into* the work, enabling true cooperative cancellation at every checkpoint.
